All the scholars referred to in these quotations adopt the Latin method, as does also Prof. Haldeman. These criticisms, therefore, reveal the lack of uniformity already noticed.

Here Prof. Haldeman takes to task every gramma- rian or writer who for some years preceding 1873 had set forth in detail his views on Roman orthoepy, and, if he makes any point at all, shows that in some partic- ular every one of them was wrong. Some reformers say that the differences noticed above are ‘⁶ insignifi- cant.’'
